## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` now throws at runtime on macOS. This is a behavioral breaking change — it still compiles fine but fails at runtime. DSA continues to work on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch algorithms — the signatures were already created with DSA. Your options:

1. **Platform-guard the code** — only run DSA verification on Windows/Linux:
   ```csharp
   if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
       throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
           "DSA verification is not supported on macOS with .NET 11+");

   using var dsa = DSA.Create();
   dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
   bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** (e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography)) that provides its own DSA implementation independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // BouncyCastle-based DSA verification works on all platforms
   var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   verifier.Init(false, publicKey);
   verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Skip macOS for this workload** — if macOS support isn't critical, gate it in CI and document the limitation.

**Recommendation:** If you must verify legacy DSA signatures on all three platforms, option 2 (BouncyCastle) is the most practical path. If macOS is only a dev environment, option 1 with a clear error message may suffice.
